                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A deeply educational read</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-09</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>It takes a good tour guide to show us a way through the dense jungle of the modern economy. What did the Southeast Asian currency crisis have to do with the USA? Why did Russian economic policy hurt Argentinean citizens? How exactly does one go about becoming a cabinet officer for the President? Robert Rubin is a knowledgable, humble tour guide par excellence. We here at History House wonder where America's economy might be in 2004 with someone of conscience and real intelligence at the helm rather than the band of thieves we got instead. Rubin's autobiography is notable for these reasons, and also because it is one of those good works which conveys important life lessons on how to get ahead, secrets of leadership, and just what's going on in our government.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Where is Robert Rubin when We Really Need Him?</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-01</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>After reading this book you will appreciate the yawning chasm that exists between the rational way economic policy was made in the Clinton years and the ideological way it is made today.  You will yearn for a Treasury Secretary who understands capital and international currency markets.  
<br />Rubin first gives a Treasury Secretary's eye view of the Mexican debt crisis, then pulls back to describe how he developed professionally to become one of two co-managing partners of arguably the best managed Wall Street firm (Goldman Sachs) before joining Clinton's economic team.  Mr. Rubin gives a sober assessment of the role of capital markets in national and international economic policy.  Only someone with his background and knowledge could pick up the phone and query a Wall Street trader on the possible repercussions of letting Mexico or Southeast Asia or Long Term Capital fail, assess the intricate interrelationships between the US and other economies, the International Monetary Fund, etc. then make the right judgment call (albeit a calculated risk) on how to respond.
<br />This book is written with modesty, intelligence and just enough personal history to let you know who Robert Rubin really is.  It is perhaps Rubin's complete lack of hubris that enables him to appreciate and understand his colleagues' points of view, sort fact from fiction (or ideology) and reach a decision that fits the situation.  It gives a sobering insight into what it takes to make good economic policy.  
<br />Try to imagine Paul O'Neill or John Snow making the same sober, informed judgment in the current ideologically driven administration - I can't. A must read for anyone who has (or wants to have) an opinion about economic policy since the millennium. 
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">objective and fair, intellectual, but intriguing</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
